\begin_layout Standard
I see JMatter as a superframework for building business applications.
 It's interesting to contrast some aspects of developing with this framework
 compared to the traditional way of coding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On many past projects with previous employers, I recall having a strong
 sense of the link between success on a software project and employee turnover.
 IT shops in general are vulnerable.
 Code can rot very quickly in environments where it's not tended, or where
 the original developer is no longer present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I believe the reason to be how quickly code becomes exceedingly complex.
 Navigating the logic of a software module or application is like finding
 your way through a labyrinth.
 Documentation is often lacking and if present, almost always out of sync
 with the actual code.
 When programmers say to each other 'the original developer left..', there
 exists between them a silent understanding of the true meaning, the business
 impact of the fact.
 It takes time and gumption to really 
\emph on
grok
\emph default
 a complex piece of software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does this have to do with JMatter? I believe JMatter dramatically simplifie
s software development.
 Take the following simple example.
 Let's say that a customer's IT shop maintains an existing JMatter application
 that was developed by an outside consulting firm.
 The customer in question needs to revise the business logic for a specific
 command.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step is to find the code.
 With a traditional application, what a new programmer will do is trace
 the code from the action's invocation in the user interface, hoping it
 will lead them to the underlying business logic where the code that needs
 to be changed resides.
 Often they discover that no such place exists! The business logic is often
 scattered throughout the path.
 Some of it may exist in the user interface, or separated across a number
 of classes that have no semblance of an object model.
 We discover that this logic is actually duplicated in a number of places.
 So the developer has to backtrack and find all places where the logic resides
 and hopefully refactor the solution before they can begin to make a change.
 They're very likely to indadvertantly break some existing logic.
\end_layout

