\begin_layout Section
Parting Thoughts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I've read many books relating to software development, or documenting various
 software frameworks.
 Many of these books do a great thing: they try to teach by example.
 And so they come up with a sample or tutorial application and throughout
 the book, make incremental changes to the tutorial application as a means
 of illustrating the workings of the framework or libraries that the book
 attempts to teach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the manual that you are reading at the moment, I have also tried to teach
 by example.
 What strikes me is that in the process we have built four applications,
 not one.
 Furthermore, I claim that the resulting applications are more functional,
 and bear more features than any of the sample applications you might encounter
 in most other books.
 This is not an attempt to boast about this manual.
 In fact our example applications were incredibly short.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I sincerely believe that JMatter is not just another framework.
 I named this framework JMatter because I felt it had tremendous substance,
 and that this work matters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anyone that's attempted to build more than one business software application
 realizes that there exist many commonalities between the various applications,
 and wishes that somehow these commonalities were refactored.
 We often find ourselves either hearing or saying
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's a simple change, except that I have to make it across 200 templates,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how can we factor these commonalities into one place so we can reuse them
 on the next project?
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most existing implementations I have seen are implemented in such a way
 that many of the supposed generic aspects of a software application are
 hopelessly tangled to the only part that I believe should change: the domain
 model.
 And so the generic parts cannot be segregated from the model, and are made
 to be written over again on the next project, only increasing the complexity
 of having to manage the various solutions we implement for our customers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since open-sourcing JMatter in June of 2006, I cannot tell you how many
 comments I've received from other developers for whom the need and desire
 for such a framework strikes a chord.
 Some have worked on their own solutions but the task is dauntingly large.
 I believe together we can make our shared vision of a better system for
 building solutions a reality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
JMatter stands on the shoulder of giants.
